Project 04

Description of Community Area

The first plot we used to describe the community area shows the population in each community area in Chicago. It is color coded on a map scale to help show areas of high population in red. We can see from the graph that Forest Glen has a particularly low population relative to other community areas in Chicago. It also borders two communities with low populations.

The second graph we used to describe the demographic of Forest Glen related unemployment to income for each community area. We found a trend line between the two variables which was negatively sloped. This is intuitive with what economics would tell us. The graph shows that Forest Glen is a relatively wealthy area with low unemployment and high income compared to the mean of communities in Chicago.

crimes %>%
  group_by(comarea) %>%
  summarize(sm_count()) %>%
  inner_join(comarea, by = "comarea") %>%
  inner_join(socio, by = "comarea") %>%
  st_as_sf() %>%
  st_transform(3436) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = population)) +
  scale_fill_distiller(trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10) +
  theme_void() +
  geom_sf(color = "blue", data = filter(comarea, comarea_name == "Forest Glen")) +
  geom_sf_label(label = "Forest Glen", data = filter(comarea, comarea_name == "Forest Glen"), nudge_y = 15000) +
  labs(title = "Population in Chicago", subtitle = "Split by comarea", color = "Population" )

socio %>% 
  ggplot(aes(income, unemployed)) +
    geom_point(color = "grey") +
    geom_point(color = "black", data = filter(socio, comarea_name == "Forest Glen")) +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
    geom_text_repel(aes(label = comarea_name), color = "black", data = filter(socio, comarea_name == "Forest Glen")) + 
    labs(title = "Income vs Unemployment Rate for Different Chicago Areas", x = "Income", y = "Unemployment Rate") 
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Crime Rate

These three graphs show us the crime rate in Forest Glen and Chicago as a whole as a function of time. We used three different graphs to plot this on a on an hourly, monthly, and yearly basis. We can see that Forest Glen’s crime rate is consistently lower than that of Chicago as a whole for all three graphs. This is probably because of the higher income demographic of Forest Glen. Looking at the hourly graph, we see a spike at midnight for both lines. This is probably because crimes that are committed at an unknown time are reported at midnight. Additionally, we see heights of crime rates for both Forest Glen and Chicago as a whole between midnight and 6:00 AM, most likely because there is a lower chance of being caught in the night. On a monthly basis the crime rate for Forest Glen peaks in May while for Chicago, it peaks in July. On a yearly basis, we observe a decline in the crime rate for both Forest Glen and Chicago over time.

crimes %>%
  filter(primary_type == "THEFT") %>%
  filter(date_iso >= "2003-01-01 00:00:00") %>%
  filter(date_iso <= "2019-12-31 23:59:59") %>%
  mutate(hour_iso = floor_date(date_iso, "1 hour")) %>%
  mutate(hour_iso = as_hms(hour_iso)) %>%
  group_by(comarea, hour_iso) %>%
  summarize(sm_count()) %>%
  mutate(area = if_else(comarea == 12, "Forest Glen", "Other")) %>%
  inner_join(socio, by = "comarea") %>%
  group_by(hour_iso, area) %>%
  summarize(crime_rate = sum(count) / sum(population)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(hour_iso, crime_rate, color = area)) +
  labs(title = "Theft Rate in Chicago Hourly Basis", subtitle = "Forest Glen versus the rest of the City",
       x = "Hour",
       y = "Theft Rate")

crimes %>%
  filter(primary_type == "THEFT") %>%
  filter(date_iso >= "2003-01-01 00:00:00") %>%
  filter(date_iso <= "2019-12-31 23:59:59") %>%
  mutate(month = month(date_iso)) %>%
  group_by(comarea, month) %>%
  summarize(sm_count()) %>%
  mutate(area = if_else(comarea == 12, "Forest Glen", "Other")) %>%
  inner_join(socio, by = "comarea") %>%
  group_by(month, area) %>%
  summarize(crime_rate = sum(count) / sum(population)) %>%
  mutate(month_date = make_date(month = month)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(month_date, crime_rate, color = area)) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = "%b") + 
  labs(title = "Theft Rate in Chicago Monthly Basis", subtitle = "Forest Glen versus the rest of the City",
       x = "Month",
       y = "Theft Rate")

crimes %>%
  filter(primary_type == "THEFT") %>%
  filter(date_iso >= "2003-01-01 00:00:00") %>%
  filter(date_iso <= "2019-12-31 23:59:59") %>%
  mutate(year = year(date_iso)) %>%
  group_by(comarea, year) %>%
  summarize(sm_count()) %>%
  mutate(area = if_else(comarea == 12, "Forest Glen", "Other")) %>%
  inner_join(socio, by = "comarea") %>%
  group_by(year, area) %>%
  summarize(crime_rate = sum(count) / sum(population)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(year, crime_rate, color = area)) +
  labs(title = "Theft Rate in Chicago Yearly Basis", subtitle = "Forest Glen versus the rest of the City",
      x = "Year",
      y = "Theft Rate")

Multivariate Analysis

The specific theft we wanted to observe was theft of dollar amount 500 dollars and under. This was the most abundant type of theft in Forest Glen, and is classified as petty theft. This makes sense because the area is relatively wealthy, thus there is less of a need to steal. We then looked at the arrest rate for under 500 dollar theft versus all theft on an hour by hour and monthly basis. In both graphs we found that under 500 dollar thefts had a lower arrest rate than all other thefts.

crimes %>%
  mutate(hour = hour(date_iso)) %>%
  mutate(type = if_else(description == "$500 AND UNDER", "$500 AND UNDER", "Other")) %>%
  group_by(hour, type, arrest) %>%
  summarize(sm_count()) %>%
  pivot_wider(values_from = count, names_from = arrest, names_prefix = "arrest_") %>%
  mutate(percentage = 100 * arrest_TRUE / (arrest_TRUE + arrest_FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(hour_hms = hms(hour = hour)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(hour_hms, percentage)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = type)) +
    geom_line(aes(color = type)) +
    labs(title = "Percentage of Hourly '$500 and Under' Theft Arrests", subtitle = "Forest Glen",
      x = "Hour",
      y = "Arrest Rate")

crimes %>%
  mutate(year = year(date_iso)) %>%
  mutate(type = if_else(description == "$500 AND UNDER", "$500 AND UNDER", "Other")) %>%
  group_by(year, type, arrest) %>%
  summarize(sm_count()) %>%
  pivot_wider(values_from = count, names_from = arrest, names_prefix = "arrest_") %>%
  mutate(percentage = 100 * arrest_TRUE / (arrest_TRUE + arrest_FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(date = make_date(year = year)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, percentage)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = type)) +
    geom_line(aes(color = type)) +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "2 year", date_labels = "%Y") +
  labs(title = "Percentage of Monthly '$500 and Under' Theft Arrests", subtitle = "Forest Glen",
      x = "Month",
      y = "Arrest Rate")

COVID-19

These graphs show theft in Forest Glen on a monthly and hourly basis respectively. We see a peak in thefts in May 2019. In 2019, the peak of thefts was at 6:00 AM. We notice, however, that we do not have significant amount of data to make conclusions about the habits of thieves in Forest Glen. We would typically expect crime to decrease due to COVID-19 in march, but this is not evident for theft given the data.

crimes %>%
  filter(primary_type == "THEFT") %>%  filter(date_iso >= "2019-01-01 00:00:00") %>%
  filter(comarea == 12) %>%
  mutate(month = month(date_iso)) %>%
  mutate(year = year(date_iso)) %>%
  group_by(month, year) %>%
  summarize(sm_count()) %>%
  mutate(date = make_date(month = month, year = year)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(date, count)) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = "%b%y") +
  labs(title = "Thefts in Forest Glen", subtitle = "From January 2019 through June 2020",
       x = "Month",
       y = "Thefts")

crimes %>%
  filter(primary_type == "THEFT") %>%
  filter(date_iso >= "2019-01-01 00:00:00") %>%
  filter(comarea == 12) %>%
  mutate(hour_iso = floor_date(date_iso, "1 hour")) %>%
  mutate(hour_iso = as_hms(hour_iso)) %>%
  mutate(year = if_else(year(date_iso) == 2019, "2019", "2020")) %>%
  group_by(year, hour_iso) %>%
  summarize(sm_count()) %>%
  mutate(hour = hour(hour_iso)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(hour, count, color = year)) +
  labs(title = "Thefts in Chicago Hourly Basis", subtitle = "Forest Glen 2019 Versus 2020",
      x = "Hour",
      y = "Thefts") +
  facet_wrap(~year)
